               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240916-267-person2289">
                  DAVID 
                  PECK
               <interp inst="t18240916-267-person2289" type="surname" value="PECK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-267-person2289" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-267-person2289" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18240916-267-viclabel1443" type="occupation">coach-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240916-267-victim2288 t18240916-267-viclabel1443"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18240916-267-crimeloc1444">Mount-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18240916-267-crimeloc1444" type="placeName" value="Mount-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18240916-267-crimeloc1444" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240916-267-off1439 t18240916-267-crimeloc1444"></join>, Grosvenor-square, in the parish of St. George's, Hanover-square. The prisoner had been in my service as <rs id="t18240916-267-deflabel1445" type="occupation">labourer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240916-267-defend2286 t18240916-267-deflabel1445"></join> for two or three years. On the 26th of August I enquired of him for some saddles and bridles; he said they were in the lumber-loft, he had put them there out of the way; I told him to go and look for them. I went up myself half an hour after, and forgetting what I had sent him for, I asked him what he did there. He said the things were not there, and he supposed they were down stairs. I came down, went out, and when I returned, I found he had gone out. He did not return. I searched the premises and missed the articles stated in the indictment; he had had them in his care. The gig harness is worth more than 40 s.; but it might have been taken separately, and the pieces would have been under that value.</p>
               <p>JONATHAN DOBSON. I got acquainted with the prisoner last May; he spoke to me about lamps, and he sent some by his little boy; I told him I would not buy of any children, and he came himself. I bought those articles of him, and hung them up in my shop, which is at No. 12, Francis-court, Wigmore-street.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240916-267-person2290">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BALLARD
               <interp inst="t18240916-267-person2290" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-267-person2290" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-267-person2290" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I did not apprehend the prisoner, but gave directions to a watchman, who apprehended him on the 25th of 
               <persName id="t18240916-267-person2291">August.</persName>
             I told him I had been looking after him for some time for stealing harness; he said he should wish to see his master. I went with him to his master's. I said,</p>
               <p>"Here is your master, will you tell him what you have done with the harness;" he then told me where the things were, and what he had got for them. Most of the articles are here: some were sold, and could not be got back again.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 46.</p>
               <p>Of <rs id="t18240916-267-verdict1446" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18240916-267-verdict1446" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-267-verdict1446" type="verdictSubcategory" value="theftunder40s"></interp>
               stealing to the value of 39 s. only
            </rs>.</p>
